<assessment id="u3_m3_meanvariance1_tutor2">
   <title>Tutor</title>
   <content>
      <p>Here again is the probability distribution of Y, the number of defective parts in an hour in Yves' production line:</p>
      <image src="../webcontent/dig003.gif"/>
   </content>
   <question id="q1">
      <body>
         <p>What is the mean of Y?	</p>
      </body>
      <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
         <choice value="Res1">2</choice>
         <choice value="Res2">.2</choice>
         <choice value="Res3">2.7</choice>
         <choice value="Res4">.54</choice>
      </multiple_choice>
      <part>
         <response match="Res1" score="0">
            <feedback>Incorrect. Your mistake is probably that you averaged the
               possible values 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, rather than taking a weighted average of the values
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T140618-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>weighted
               by their corresponding
               probabilities<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T140621-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>.
               Review the definition of the mean of a random variable (on this page), and try again. </feedback>
         </response>
         <response match="Res2" score="0">
            <feedback>Incorrect. Your mistake is probably that you averaged the
               probabilities rather than taking a weighted average of the values
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T140641-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>weighted
               by their corresponding
               probabilities<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T140644-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>.
               Review the definition of the mean of a random variable (on this page), and try
               again.</feedback>
         </response>
         <response match="Res3" score="10">
            <feedback>Good
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T140653-0500"?>j<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T140652-0500" content="J"?>ob!
               Indeed, the mean of Y is 0(.05) + 1(.05) + 2(.10) + 3(.75) + 4(.05) = 2.7.</feedback>
         </response>
         <response match="Res4" score="0">
            <feedback>Incorrect. Your mistake is probably that you found the weighted
               average of the values
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T140708-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>weighted
               by their corresponding probabilities<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T140718-0500"?>),<?oxy_insert_end?>
               <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T140714-0500" content="("?>as you
               should<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T140724-0500" content=")"?>,
               but then you divided it by 5, which is incorrect. The division already occurred when
               the probabilities were determined. The mean of a random variable
               <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T140750-0500" comment="use italics rather than all caps for emphasis"?>IS<?oxy_comment_end?>
               that weighted average. Please try again.</feedback>
         </response>
      </part>
   </question>
